{"title_page": "Black Sunday (storm)", "text_new": "[[File:Wea01422.jpg|thumb|right|The \"Black Sunday\" dust storm approaches [[Spearman, Texas|Spearman]] in northern [[Texas]], April 14, 1935.]]\n'''Black Sunday''' refers to a particularly severe [[dust storm]] that occurred on April 14, 1935, as part of the [[Dust Bowl]].<ref name=\"nws\">{{cite web|title=The Black Sunday Dust Storm of 14 April 1935|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/oun/?n=blacksunday|publisher=National Weather Service: Norman, Oklahoma Weather Forecast Office|accessdate=23 May 2012}}</ref> It was one of the worst dust storms in American history and it caused immense economic and agricultural damage.<ref name=\"pbs\">{{cite web|title=Black Sunday: April 14, 1935|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/americanexperience/features/general-article/dustbowl-black-sunday|publisher=PBS|accessdate=24 May 2012}}</ref> It is estimated to have displaced 300&nbsp;million tons of [[topsoil]] from the prairie area in the US.<ref>''Black Blizzard'', History Channel documentary.</ref>\n\nOn the afternoon of April 14, the residents of the [[Plains States]] were forced to take cover as a dust storm, or \"black blizzard\", blew through the region. The storm hit the [[Oklahoma Panhandle]] and [[Northwestern Oklahoma]] first, and moved south for the remainder of the day.<ref name=\"nws\"/> It hit [[Beaver, Oklahoma|Beaver]] around 4:00&nbsp;p.m., [[Boise City, Oklahoma|Boise City]] around 5:15&nbsp;p.m., and [[Amarillo, Texas]], at 7:20&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=\"nws\"/> The conditions were the most severe in the Oklahoma and [[Texas panhandle]]s, but the storm's effects were felt in other surrounding areas.<ref name=\"nws\"/>\n\nThe storm was harsh due to the high winds that hit the area that day. The combination of drought, erosion, bare soil, and winds caused the dust to fly freely and at high speeds.<ref name=\"ncdc\">{{cite web|title=The Dust Bowl Drought|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/paleo/drought/drght_history.html|work=Drought: A Paleo Perspective -- 20th Century Drought|accessdate=24 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n== The Dust Bowl ==\n{{Main|Dust Bowl}}\nIn North America, the term \"Dust Bowl\" was first used to describe a series of dust storms that hit the [[prairie]]s of [[Canada]] and the [[United States]] during the 1930s,<ref name=\"ncdc\"/> and later to describe the area in the United States that was most affected by the storms, including western Kansas, eastern Colorado, northeastern New Mexico, and the Oklahoma and Texas panhandles.<ref name=\"histevents\">{{cite web|title=Dust Bowl 1931\u20131939|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/article-1G2-3424800020/dust-bowl-1931-1939.html|work=Historic Events for Students: The Great Depression|publisher=Encyclopedia.com|accessdate=22 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe \"black blizzards\" started in the Eastern states in 1930, affecting agriculture from [[Maine]] to [[Arkansas]]. By 1934 they had reached the [[Great Plains]], stretching from North Dakota to Texas, and from the [[Mississippi embayment|Mississippi River Valley]] to the [[Rocky Mountains]].<ref name=\"watkins\">{{cite book|last=Watkins|first=T. H.|title=The Dust Bowl|year=2003|publisher=Greenhaven Press|chapter=Prosperity, Depression, and War: 1920\u20131945|pages=162\u2013170}}</ref> \"The Dust Bowl\" (as an area) received its name following the disastrous \"Black Sunday\" storm in April 1935, when reporter Robert E. Geiger referred to the region as \"The Dust Bowl\" in his account of the storm.<ref name=\"histevents\"/>\n\n== Causes ==\n{{Details|Dust Bowl#Causes}}\n\n[[Cattle]] farming and [[Sheep husbandry|sheep ranching]] had left much of the West devoid of natural grass and shrubs to anchor the soil,<ref name=\"histevents\"/> and over-farming and poor soil stewardship left the soil dehydrated and lacking in organic matter.<ref name=\"watkins\"/> During a massive [[drought]] that hit the United States in the 1930s,<ref name=\"histevents\"/> the lack of rainfall, snowfall, and moisture in the air dried out the top soil in most of the country's farming regions.\n\n== Effects ==\nThe destruction caused by the dust storms, and especially by the storm on Black Sunday, killed multiple people {{Citation needed|date=April 2018}} and caused hundreds of thousands of people to relocate.<ref name=\"watkins\"/> Poor migrants from the American Southwest (known as \"[[Okie]]s\" - though only about 20 percent were from Oklahoma) flooded California, overtaxing the state's health and employment infrastructure.<ref name=\"howstuffworks\">{{cite web|last=Trimarchi|first=Maria|title=What Caused the Dust Bowl?|url=http://science.howstuffworks.com/environmental/green-science/dust-bowl-cause2.html|publisher=HowStuffWorks|accessdate=19 May 2012|date=2008-09-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 1935, after the massive damage caused by these storms, Congress passed the [[Soil Conservation and Domestic Allotment Act of 1936|Soil Conservation Act]], which established the [[Natural Resources Conservation Service|Soil Conservation Service]] (SCS) as a permanent agency of the [[United States Department of Agriculture|USDA]].<ref>{{cite web|title=USDA Is Celebrating 150 Years|url=http://www.in.nrcs.usda.gov|publisher=Indiana NRCS|accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> The SCS was created in an attempt to provide guidance for land owners and land users to reduce soil erosion, improve forest and field land and conserve and develop natural resources.<ref name=\"howstuffworks\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=NRCS Fact Sheet |url=http://www.me.nrcs.usda.gov/about/FactSheet.html |publisher=Maine NCRS |accessdate=20 May 2012 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130214164232/http://www.me.nrcs.usda.gov/about/FactSheet.html |archivedate=14 February 2013 }}</ref>  This led to the [[Great Plains Shelterbelt]] project.\n\n== Personal accounts of Black Sunday and other dust storms ==\nDuring the 1930s, many residents of the Dust Bowl kept accounts and journals of their lives and of the storms that hit their areas. Collections of accounts of the dust storms during the 1930s have been compiled over the years and are now available in book collections and online.\n\n{{quote|text=\"People caught in their own yards grope for the doorstep. Cars come to a standstill, for no light in the world can penetrate that swirling murk\u2026. The nightmare is deepest during the storms. But on the occasional bright day and the usual gray day we cannot shake from it. We live with the dust, eat it, sleep with it, watch it strip us of possessions and the hope of possessions.\"<ref name=\"pbs\"/>|sign=Avis D. Carlson|source=[[The New Republic]]}}\n\nLawrence Svobida was a [[wheat]] farmer in Kansas during the 1930s.<ref name=\"histevents\"/>  He experienced the period of dust storms, and the effect that they had on the surrounding environment and the society.<ref name=\"histevents\"/> His observations and feelings are available in his memoirs, ''Farming the Dust Bowl''.<ref name=\"histevents\"/> Here he describes an approaching dust storm:\n\n{{quote|text=\"\u2026 At other times a cloud is seen to be approaching from a distance of many miles. Already it has the banked appearance of a cumulus cloud, but it is black instead of white and it hangs low, seeming to hug the earth. Instead of being slow to change its form, it appears to be rolling on itself from the crest downward. As it sweeps onward, the landscape is progressively blotted out. Birds fly in terror before the storm, and only those that are strong of wing may escape. The smaller birds fly until they are exhausted, then fall to the ground, to share the fate of the thousands of jack rabbits which perish from suffocation.\"<ref name=\"histevents\"/>}}\n\nThe Black Sunday storm is detailed in the 2012 [[Ken Burns]] PBS documentary ''[[The Dust Bowl (film)|The Dust Bowl]]''.\n\n== In popular culture ==\n\nMusicians and songwriters began to reflect the Dust Bowl and the events of the 1930s in their music. [[Woody Guthrie]], a singer-songwriter from Oklahoma, wrote a variety of songs documenting his experiences living during the era of dust storms.<ref name=\"nws\"/> Several were collected in his first album ''[[Dust Bowl Ballads]]''. One of them, ''Great Dust Storm'', describes the events of Black Sunday.  An excerpt of the lyrics follows:\n\n''On the 14th day of April of 1935,<br />\n''There struck the worst of dust storms that ever filled the sky.<br />\n''You could see that dust storm comin', the cloud looked deathlike black,<br />\n''And through our mighty nation, it left a dreadful track.<br />\n''From Oklahoma City to the Arizona line,<br />\n''Dakota and Nebraska to the lazy Rio Grande,<br />\n''It fell across our city like a curtain of black rolled down,<br />\n''We thought it was our judgement, we thought it was our doom.<ref name=\"nws\"/>\n\nMusician Kat Eggleston has written a play, ''The Cyclone Line'', about her father Al Eggleston's experiences growing up in 1930s Oklahoma, Black Sunday, and the Dust Bowl in general. Its first public performances were on [[Vashon, Washington|Vashon (Island), Washington]], where he lived most of his life.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://vashonalliedarts.org/the-cyclone-line-a-play-by-kat-eggleston/|title=The Cyclone Line, a play by Kat Eggleston \u00ab Vashon Center for the Arts|website=vashonalliedarts.org|access-date=November 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161103235016/http://vashonalliedarts.org/the-cyclone-line-a-play-by-kat-eggleston/|archive-date=November 3, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\nAmericana recording artist [[Grant Maloy Smith]] released an album in 2017 called ''Dust Bowl \u2013 American Stories'' that featured two songs that directly referenced Black Sunday. The song \"Old Black Roller\" is written from a first person perspective during the Black Sunday storm, and another song \"Never Seen The Rain\" has these chorus lyrics: \"We worked the land to death, me and my brother | 'Til April 14, 1935 | Oklahoma, you were like our mother - oh, my\"\n\nAmerican recording artist [[Gillian Welch]] refers to the storm and other historical events in a two-part song on her 2001 album ''[[Time (The Revelator)]]'': \"April the 14th Part I\" and \"Ruination Day Part II\".\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Droughts in the United States]]\n[[Category:Dust storms]]\n[[Category:Weather hazards]]\n[[Category:Dust Bowl]]\n[[Category:1935 natural disasters in the United States]]\n[[Category:1935 in Texas]]\n[[Category:Natural disasters in Texas]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Wea01422.jpg|thumb|right|The \"Black Sunday\" dust storm approaches [[Spearman, Texas|Spearman]] in northern [[Texas]], April 14, 1935.]]\n'''Black Sunday''' refers to a particularly severe [[dust storm]] that occurred on April 14, 1935, as part of the [[Dust Bowl]].<ref name=\"nws\">{{cite web|title=The Black Sunday Dust Storm of 14 April 1935|url=http://www.srh.noaa.gov/oun/?n=blacksunday|publisher=National Weather Service: Norman, Oklahoma Weather Forecast Office|accessdate=23 May 2012}}</ref> It was one of the worst dust storms in American history and it caused immense economic and agricultural damage.<ref name=\"pbs\">{{cite web|title=Black Sunday: April 14, 1935|url=https://www.pbs.org/wgbh/americanexperience/features/general-article/dustbowl-black-sunday|publisher=PBS|accessdate=24 May 2012}}</ref> It is estimated to have displaced 300 million tons of [[topsoil]] from the prairie area in the US.<ref>''Black Blizzard'', History Channel documentary.</ref>\n\nOn the afternoon of April 14, the residents of the [[Plains States]] were forced to take cover as a dust storm, or \"black blizzard\", blew through the region. The storm hit the [[Oklahoma Panhandle]] and [[Northwestern Oklahoma]] first, and moved south for the remainder of the day.<ref name=\"nws\"/> It hit [[Beaver, Oklahoma|Beaver]] around 4:00&nbsp;p.m., [[Boise City, Oklahoma|Boise City]] around 5:15&nbsp;p.m., and [[Amarillo, Texas]], at 7:20&nbsp;p.m.<ref name=\"nws\"/> The conditions were the most severe in the Oklahoma and [[Texas panhandle]]s, but the storm's effects were felt in other surrounding areas.<ref name=\"nws\"/>\n\nThe storm was harsh due to the high winds that hit the area that day. The combination of drought, erosion, bare soil, and winds caused the dust to fly freely and at high speeds.<ref name=\"ncdc\">{{cite web|title=The Dust Bowl Drought|url=http://www.ncdc.noaa.gov/paleo/drought/drght_history.html|work=Drought: A Paleo Perspective -- 20th Century Drought|accessdate=24 May 2012}}</ref>\n\n== The Dust Bowl ==\n{{Main|Dust Bowl}}\nIn North America, the term \"Dust Bowl\" was first used to describe a series of dust storms that hit the [[prairie]]s of [[Canada]] and the [[United States]] during the 1930s,<ref name=\"ncdc\"/> and later to describe the area in the United States that was most affected by the storms, including western Kansas, eastern Colorado, northeastern New Mexico, and the Oklahoma and Texas panhandles.<ref name=\"histevents\">{{cite web|title=Dust Bowl 1931\u20131939|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/article-1G2-3424800020/dust-bowl-1931-1939.html|work=Historic Events for Students: The Great Depression|publisher=Encyclopedia.com|accessdate=22 May 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe \"black blizzards\" started in the Eastern states in 1930, affecting agriculture from [[Maine]] to [[Arkansas]]. By 1934 they had reached the [[Great Plains]], stretching from North Dakota to Texas, and from the [[Mississippi embayment|Mississippi River Valley]] to the [[Rocky Mountains]].<ref name=\"watkins\">{{cite book|last=Watkins|first=T. H.|title=The Dust Bowl|year=2003|publisher=Greenhaven Press|chapter=Prosperity, Depression, and War: 1920\u20131945|pages=162\u2013170}}</ref> \"The Dust Bowl\" (as an area) received its name following the disastrous \"Black Sunday\" storm in April 1935, when reporter Robert E. Geiger referred to the region as \"The Dust Bowl\" in his account of the storm.<ref name=\"histevents\"/>\n\n== Causes ==\n{{Details|Dust Bowl#Causes}}\n\n[[Cattle]] farming and [[Sheep husbandry|sheep ranching]] had left much of the West devoid of natural grass and shrubs to anchor the soil,<ref name=\"histevents\"/> and over-farming and poor soil stewardship left the soil dehydrated and lacking in organic matter.<ref name=\"watkins\"/> During a massive [[drought]] that hit the United States in the 1930s,<ref name=\"histevents\"/> the lack of rainfall, snowfall, and moisture in the air dried out the top soil in most of the country's farming regions.\n\n== Effects ==\nThe destruction caused by the dust storms, and especially by the storm on Black Sunday, killed multiple people {{Citation needed|date=April 2018}} and caused hundreds of thousands of people to relocate<ref name=\"watkins\"/>. Poor migrants from the American Southwest (known as \"[[Okie]]s\" - though only about 20 percent were from Oklahoma) flooded California, overtaxing the state's health and employment infrastructure.<ref name=\"howstuffworks\">{{cite web|last=Trimarchi|first=Maria|title=What Caused the Dust Bowl?|url=http://science.howstuffworks.com/environmental/green-science/dust-bowl-cause2.html|publisher=HowStuffWorks|accessdate=19 May 2012|date=2008-09-17}}</ref>\n\nIn 1935, after the massive damage caused by these storms, Congress passed the [[Soil Conservation and Domestic Allotment Act of 1936|Soil Conservation Act]], which established the [[Natural Resources Conservation Service|Soil Conservation Service]] (SCS) as a permanent agency of the [[United States Department of Agriculture|USDA]].<ref>{{cite web|title=USDA Is Celebrating 150 Years|url=http://www.in.nrcs.usda.gov|publisher=Indiana NRCS|accessdate=19 May 2012}}</ref> The SCS was created in an attempt to provide guidance for land owners and land users to reduce soil erosion, improve forest and field land and conserve and develop natural resources.<ref name=\"howstuffworks\"/><ref>{{cite web|title=NRCS Fact Sheet |url=http://www.me.nrcs.usda.gov/about/FactSheet.